Cell[TextData[{
 "There is a graphical problem here with no clearly preferable solution. \
Because world lines in relativity will have a slope less than ",
 Cell[BoxData["1"],ExpressionUUID->"74d603b7-74dc-4b44-9bf1-01b81d7052ab"],
 " from the t axis, spacetime diagrams tend to get stretched out in the \
vertical direction. If we want the plot to stay on one notebook page we will \
have to keep the plot narrow. We could change the aspect ratio of the \
spacetime diagram but then light lines will no longer be at 45\[Degree], \
contrary to textbook tradition, nor will areas be faithfully represented. If \
we make the animation a simple projection onto the x axis then it will be \
cramped. I've decided to use an expanded scale for the animation to make \
better use of the notebook page. "
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ca000815-d3f4-4586-9908-33c29f1b246d"],

Cell["\<\
A straight line on a spacetime diagram represents the inertial motion of a \
particle through space. The bottom plot clearly shows the motion. In textbook \
spacetime diagrams the moving time slice and point are missing. They are \
included here to key to the motion animation at the bottom. When you view a \
spacetime diagram in a textbook, try to visualize the corresponding animation.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"916ff888-dbcf-4a39-a8f4-3ff8a7d73a58"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For this case the velocity of the particle is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[CapitalDelta]x", "/", "\[CapitalDelta]t"}], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"1", "/", "2"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ff929171-5e15-4aa8-beef-3cc39cb80136"],
 ". The velocity is the inverse slope of the line."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cc95f4cb-1373-4b63-9f3e-c852556a1fe8"],

Cell["\<\
All the spacetime diagrams and animations in this notebook, and generally in \
textbooks, have at least an implied stationary observer that represents a \
vertical line in the spacetime diagram. An implied stationary observer also \
exists for the animation at the bottom, even though he or she is not always \
explicitly shown.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6c8f693e-31d4-4716-9536-7e8dcb4e344c"],

Cell["\<\
Blue or green circles will generally be used to represent the motion of \
massive particles, objects or observers and red circles and lines will be \
used for photons.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"78620387-6125-40a7-98ef-b910ace19177"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.2 Measuring Instruments and Proper Time", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"1b21b02f-b22a-4568-92d8-ae67515a7bc0"],

Cell["\<\
To make spacetime measurements we will use
1) Clocks,
2) Photon sources that provide photons of a specific energy,
3) Photon detectors that could alternatively measure the photon energy.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"51eebf17-fd22-4991-80a4-c39ec0619f55"],

Cell["\<\
We won't use any meter sticks. All of the clocks, photon sources and photon \
detectors are made to standard specification and we will consider them to \
have whatever accuracy we need. The energy of a photon is directly related to \
the frequency of the associated wave. The reason we want to be able to \
measure frequency is to measure relative velocity by the Doppler effect if \
necessary.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7273d4c8-ba43-4f7b-8b56-1420021b0eeb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In Newtonian physics there is one universal time, but in relativity each \
set of observers in parallel motion keep their own time. This own time is \
called ",
 StyleBox["proper time",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". This does not mean that other times are somehow improper, but rather \
comes from the French word 'proper', which means personal or belonging to \
oneself. Taylor and Wheeler (3) call this 'wristwatch time'. It is what each \
person reads by consulting his own wristwatch."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c5a8c986-c8b5-4505-9bea-c745d3f763b3"],

Cell["\<\
Proper time will be indicated in spacetime diagrams and animations in a \
framed box that follows the particles. Often the wristwatch will be used as a \
stopwatch and simply record the time intervals between certain events. \
Sometimes, but not always, on spacetime diagrams proper times will be put in \
circles.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e1467302-571e-4eff-92f9-9fafb6408794"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the Euclidean plane the distance between two points is just the length \
of the straight line between the points. We could measure it with a ruler and \
if we knew the horizontal and vertical distances between the two points we \
could calculate the length using the Pythagorean theorem. ",
 StyleBox["We are very used to interpreting plane diagrams in terms of \
Euclidean geometry; but spacetime has a different geometry!",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "  We have to learn how to read spacetime diagrams and translate them into \
spacetime physics. It takes a little practice."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ef4f8eab-0d80-4150-b4e7-78a314ff6dce"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In spacetime physics the distance between two events on a line representing \
an inertial observer will be that observer's elapsed proper time (wristwatch \
time). Proper time will generally be denoted by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"cf5527c5-fdc2-4abb-ac52-f22d2dcc6793"],
 " or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"34287f29-3cb5-496c-8beb-d928895a1170"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"59e45dca-d060-4418-a7a3-61cc6d98800a"],
 " if we are discussing proper times on two different world lines. If we have \
used ",
 Cell[BoxData["x"],ExpressionUUID->"aa5817e7-e0cb-460a-a053-884326f40c04"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["t"],ExpressionUUID->"d3037f41-5cd9-4fd2-829a-324384861b34"],
 " coordinates in a spacetime diagram, it is easy to forget that proper time \
is not the same as ",
 Cell[BoxData["t"],ExpressionUUID->"0c45a210-7cab-4969-8aa2-37a6b269b6f0"],
 ". In many of our diagrams we will not even show ",
 Cell[BoxData["x"],ExpressionUUID->"1337cd1f-7149-426e-98a1-e3add4430c26"],
 " or ",
 Cell[BoxData["t"],ExpressionUUID->"8e234004-7f81-42fa-acdf-3199017b432f"],
 ". One of our problems is to learn how to relate proper times on different \
inertial lines. The following animation is a repeat of the second animation \
in Section 2.1 but this time with the proper time clock shown for the moving \
object."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4f032456-84f5-4ba1-aefa-f1e24072cd22"],

