}, {2}]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For our experiment we have bought two identical super accurate photon \
velocity meters from Photon Industries. The first detector is at rest and the \
second detector is boosted to a velocity of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "4"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bba2139b-3b9e-4cda-a80e-cddeb9e10a89"],
 " the speed of light. A photon is released from the right and successively \
passes through each of the detectors."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2e8ec08a-537f-451b-8e82-814b1834e68e"],

Cell["\<\
Surprise! Both meters read exactly the same velocity. One of the detectors is \
moving toward the oncoming photon, so we might expect it to see a higher \
velocity than the stationary detector.  What actually happens, as shown by \
experiment, is that both detectors record exactly the same velocity. \
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"659cff6c-f666-4e5b-8768-67ab27bca832"],

Cell["\<\
The original experiment that checked this was the Kennedy-Thorndike \
experiment. You can read about a modern version of this experiment on the web \
at: \
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7b89e35f-e5e2-4e5a-88bc-fae3c65a62fa"],

Cell[TextData[{
 " ",
 ButtonBox[" http://qom.physik.hu-berlin.de/research_kt.htm",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData:>{
    URL["http://qom.physik.hu-berlin.de/research_kt.htm"], None}]
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"03b17bf4-2968-40aa-8c78-6ba9dbdb4a9b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "On the other hand, maybe it is not so surprising. The Maxwell equations \
have one fundamental constant, ",
 Cell[BoxData["c"],ExpressionUUID->"d5cdb4d6-f90b-4857-8113-1127541ce581"],
 ", the speed of light, and the theory makes no reference to any preferred \
inertial frame. The idea that the theory should be tied to some specific \
frame is a modification of Maxwell's laws and is referred to as an \"emission\
\" theory. But Kennedy-Thorndike shows that these theories are incorrect."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"12898e00-7ffb-494d-bdc4-5650ff5c216a"],

Cell["\<\
The first postulate of special relativity is truly astonishing. It is what \
makes spacetime geometry different than Euclidean geometry. It is not \
intuitive because in our common experience we don't interact with other \
objects that are traveling near the speed of light. However, if you become an \
experimental physicist in even moderately high energy physics the situation \
changes, and so will your intuition.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ee1d5dd6-1218-425f-a0ab-95b3f7b97508"],

Cell["\<\
If the second postulate weren't true, experiments could never be repeated or \
confirmed by someone else at another place. Engineering would never work. \
Section 2.4 on Spacetime Translations relates this postulate to the geometry \
of spacetime.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b027a8ef-60a8-4e70-9f7c-7b78c93d805f"],

Cell["\<\
I am not aware at the moment of direct experiments to test the limits of the \
third postulate. Certainly any gross violation would have been noticed by \
now. In the paper by Brill and Jacobson, and the paper by Mermin, this is the \
specific requirement that they cover with 'the principle of relativity'. \
Section 2.5 on Bondi Triangles and the Doppler Effect relates this postulate \
to the geometry of spacetime.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4d23567f-b987-426d-a45f-ed8f36fbf853"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The invariance of the speed of light endows the spacetime plane with unique \
properties not shared by the Euclidean plane. The ",
 StyleBox["directions",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " of the worldlines of photons in the spacetime planes must remain constant. \
The following diagram shows this."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"af040da1-fdb9-4e90-a878-d4d7684ac5ee"],

