Cell[TextData[{
 "Notice that it is the direction, and not the length, of a photon world line \
in the spacetime plane that determines its velocity. That is why arrows were \
used in the diagram above and they were given random lengths. Stretching or \
shrinking the arrows is permissible, but changing their directions violates \
the first postulate of special relativity. There are two privileged \
directions corresponding to forward traveling photons and backward traveling \
photons. These directions are also sometimes called ",
 StyleBox["null directions",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " or ",
 StyleBox["null rays",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0f6bd414-0a40-4afe-b829-2e99bda0ec62"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Although it is open to choice as to how to orient a spacetime diagram on a \
piece of paper and at what angle the null rays should intersect, the almost \
universal convention is to have the forward traveling light ray at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"45", "\[Degree]"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d8a16c0c-4864-400e-895c-354d50e2be2c"],
 " and the backward traveling light ray at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"135", "\[Degree]"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "89d17a8a-ac7b-4f75-947c-f63b45dce81e"],
 ".  This corresponds to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"c", "\[Equal]", "1"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4cb4c1c0-e80e-4d24-8daf-e24175e56544"],
 " and a stationary object moving upward on a vertical line."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"125c8c2d-bc8f-445b-a1ff-bfdb065b705d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So, the first postulate tells us how to draw null rays in spacetime \
diagrams. We ",
 StyleBox["always",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " draw them at angles of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "45"}], "\[Degree]"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8c5e55a1-31ee-4ace-9b4d-408260666bfb"],
 " (slopes of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d1261d2b-5454-4e01-bdc6-181dacca82f7"],
 ") regardless of which observer is stationary in the frame."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0a76c8b1-84d9-4be2-b2b8-a4c0eea639ce"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.4 Spacetime Translations", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"c9fc4758-9014-4018-9155-4886455c148c"],

Cell["\<\
All other conditions being the same, if we do a physics experiment now or a \
year from now, we expect to get the same result. All physics experiments seem \
to be repeatable in time. This is quite solidly confirmed by experience.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"93fc41c1-4dda-48bb-a6b1-b546e260057b"],

Cell["\<\
All other conditions being the same, if we do a physics experiment here or \
somewhere else, we expect to get the same result. All physics experiments \
seem to be repeatable at different locations. This also is quite solidly \
confirmed by experience.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c1717e42-665a-4500-bc1b-1d07a1a63e17"],

Cell["\<\
So spacetime, like the Euclidean plane, is invariant under translations. \
Euclidean geometry and spacetime geometry share this property.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ee56a49e-1516-42ce-8561-a8139ab768ca"],

Cell["\<\
This symmetry under translation in space and time endows spacetime lines with \
a special property. Consider the following animation.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d04629a7-0b98-488f-bf83-19cdf43fe5fd"],

