Cell[TextData[{
 "As an inertial observer moves along his world line, his wristwatch ticks \
out equal time intervals. The ticking clock uniformly graduates the spacetime \
line. (Such a line in geometry is sometimes called an ",
 StyleBox["affine line",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".)",
 " ",
 StyleBox["Equal",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " time intervals on the wristwatch are associated with ",
 StyleBox["equal",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " Euclidean distances on the line. Think of walking in a straight line at a \
uniform pace across your office floor. Each footfall marks out the same time \
interval on your wristwatch. It also marks out the same Euclidean distance \
along your line of walk. And this means it marks out the same Euclidean \
distance on the spacetime diagram."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e54948bf-03e2-4a05-b25a-bf8fa782c366"],

Cell["This is very important and useful so we will emphasize it.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e3a4e1bf-dc52-4e43-bcd2-07bf75847e0d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Along any given inertial line in spacetime, elapsed proper time is \
proportional to Euclidean distance. ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"s", " ", "d"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "41e6a427-ffda-45d0-9ee0-9f8d2fc8cb6d"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData["s"],ExpressionUUID->"683317c6-1f50-4892-a401-cd8d690d8b0f"],
 " is a constant specific to the inertial line."
}], "Text",
 CellFrame->True,
 FontFamily->"Helvetica",
 FontSize->16,
 FontWeight->"Bold",
 FontSlant->"Plain",ExpressionUUID->"1bc65d5a-da71-46d8-b1f2-e3660698b452"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "But ",
 Cell[BoxData["s"],ExpressionUUID->"8e45966f-03b7-4f4a-979c-fd141f3c3e4b"],
 " will be different on different lines."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5871171d-8368-4aad-8518-1a99f725017d"],

Cell["\<\
Just as the first postulate told us how to draw null lines on any spacetime \
diagram, the second postulate tells us how Euclidean distances and proper \
times are related along any given inertial line. It means that on a given \
inertial line we can always replace a ratio of Euclidean distances by the \
ratio of the corresponding clock intervals.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5bbac397-de46-453b-934e-7fc1c42d2846"],

Cell["\<\
It even tells us how to relate time intervals on two parallel lines. All we \
have to do is translate one line to the other parallel line. The time \
intervals will be the same by the second postulate.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5120a0f2-b486-40b1-830e-ec7f9df4057f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We do not yet know how to relate Euclidean distances and clock times on \
inertial lines that are not parallel. Note that in Euclidean geometry, if we \
had a proof diagram drawn on a piece of paper, we could rotate the diagram \
(keeping the paper fixed) and the proof would still be valid. Geometry in the \
Euclidean plane is invariant to rotations about any point. If this were true \
of spacetime, then we could find the point where two inertial lines \
intersected and rotate one into the other. Then supposedly the time intervals \
would be the same. ",
 StyleBox["But this is the one thing that we can't do in spacetime",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". If we rotated the diagrams, that would also rotate the null directions \
and the first postulate says that we can't change the directions of the null \
lines. Therefore, if we were to somehow change the direction of an inertial \
line, which corresponds to changing its velocity with respect to a stationary \
observer, we can't expect the proper time spacings to remain the same."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c4fd8f8d-0ecb-4193-aa12-eb549b91debe"],

Cell["\<\
Bondi triangles and the third postulate will tell us how to get from one \
inertial line to another.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ae9c509c-1abc-4292-89a1-1104a2a02eb1"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.5 Bondi Triangles and Doppler Shifts", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"b1332fff-de6b-4d92-82e4-be4ee0ccf2d7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Our third postulate for special relativity is geometrically related to ",
 StyleBox["Bondi triangles",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and the ",
 StyleBox["Bondi factor",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". I haven't seen the term Bondi triangle directly mentioned in the \
literature but Bondi factors are always associated with the same type of \
triangle in the spacetime plane and so I am going to use that term to refer \
to them."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"380190a8-ba3e-415f-b27c-addaa8c9de9c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Evaluate the following cell for the definition of a ",
 StyleBox["Bondi triangle",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and the ",
 StyleBox["Bondi k",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " ",
 StyleBox["factor",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fdc2acfb-45fa-499b-9f10-32f42ee4033d"],

