Cell[TextData[{
 "Two inertial observers cross paths when their respective clocks are both \
set to zero. After a proper time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"c09275fb-114f-45d4-978d-e9003ecef3a8"],
 " the left observer sends a photon to the right observer. The right observer \
receives the photon at time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"k", " ", "\[Sigma]"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9e273d1b-60ae-4700-9da7-ed0cb676f7c9"],
 " on his clock. ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"fe1f178d-288f-4a90-ac56-3dbe17f45cd2"],
 " is called the ",
 StyleBox["Bondi factor ",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "for this pair of inertial lines and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "O\[Sigma]\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"e6e1c8b0-f7b1-4ae2-bd93-320f8fa6b52a"],
 " is called a ",
 StyleBox["Bondi triangle",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ". Notice that two legs of a Bondi triangle are inertial lines and the other \
side is a light line. Here we have used the proper time clocks as stop \
watches. They record the time, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"3b81770d-92b7-4827-b9af-4c55d2653e40"],
 ", after crossing when the first observer emits the photon on his clock and \
the time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"7db8491b-84ff-4764-80ba-7b848d6b5b84"],
 " when the second observer receives the photon on his clock. Euclidean \
distance along either line will be proportional to the proper time along that \
line (symmetry of translation) but the proportionality factors are different \
for the two lines. Let's explore this more carefully to see how we get from \
the Euclidean diagram to the spacetime interpretation. Let ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]e"],ExpressionUUID->"b0b8327e-a8fd-4656-8fbb-f638453b3fbd"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]e"],ExpressionUUID->"180c05f1-2044-464c-b702-f8dbe54faa79"],
 " be the Euclidean distances from ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"],ExpressionUUID->"37d141f7-c8d9-4840-90cc-af280b9f58de"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"1045c0b2-a0aa-4fc6-ba3f-b42b8d695825"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"76175f5f-b33e-44d4-885f-9469a40c49b8"],
 " on the diagram. By symmetry of translation we can write ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Sigma]", "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"s1", " ", "\[Sigma]e"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "df7f737f-c8eb-4ee0-a770-b111332f5dfc"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"s2", " ", "\[Tau]e"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "508e4cd8-2a42-492c-ac5a-d2aecb237c4c"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData["s1"],ExpressionUUID->"0d52e661-bfc8-4486-8243-907b49bcbc5a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["s2"],ExpressionUUID->"4eb06b48-7415-47d1-8716-1927821065a7"],
 " are the proportionality factors for each of the world lines. All possible \
pairs of Euclidean points ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]e"],ExpressionUUID->"0a251bb2-1112-4d08-8b6b-2d0f7ee96f6f"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]e"],ExpressionUUID->"8c9537bf-a8a7-4a50-b167-b98af5d2ba13"],
 " will be connected by parallel light lines. (See the next animation on \
Doppler shift for an example of a set of such triangles.) Then by similar \
Euclidean triangles ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Tau]e", "/", "\[Sigma]e"}], "\[Equal]", " ", "constant"}]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7f73a31a-b88d-4fc1-8327-c1efe79f5bc2"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "/", "\[Sigma]"}], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"s2", " ", "\[Tau]e"}], ")"}], "/", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"s1", " ", "\[Sigma]e"}], ")"}]}], "\[Equal]", "k"}]],
  ExpressionUUID->"46439769-0097-4004-89e4-da2045b8534a"],
 " a constant."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ff5489db-b2bc-4189-8f46-e4fedfa42f10"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that the Bondi factor relates two inertial world lines that cross. \
Pairs of lines that cross at different angles, i.e., have different relative \
velocities, will have different ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"3163ff34-97e1-48cf-97bd-4a95ebbd584b"],
 " factors."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a010c929-5e24-42f6-abb0-96d5c7788051"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If the blue observer was carrying a large clock and the green observer \
looked at him, then at time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"3cdb5da1-4b98-4063-9135-a3b16e29f442"],
 " on his clock he would see the blue clock displaying the time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"bee1ebcf-6aa4-47bb-a7d9-f147e67e3857"],
 ". We say that the past is behind us and that the future lies before us. The \
ancient Greeks said the opposite and were more nearly correct. Whichever \
direction you are facing, you see the past. When you look in a mirror you see \
yourself several nanoseconds ago. You see the sun as it was eight minutes \
ago. If you use one of our powerful telescopes you see galaxies as they were \
billions of years ago. The past is in front of us and we don't see the future \
at all."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dc601bc4-8e47-420a-8840-c4fd8c3e6044"],

