  RowBox[{"0", " ", 
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "1"], 
   SubscriptBox["\[Tau]", "2"]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2d4d3125-fb48-4adc-b7c6-78fccf0427df"],
 " are called ",
 StyleBox["Minkowski similar triangles",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " by Brill and Jacobson. (They are not generally similar in Euclidean \
space.)  All Bondi triangles with a common vertex and common timelike sides \
are Minkowski similar."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"28285423-2ba1-44e4-8484-8f2c55cb99f0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So now our three postulates tell us how to make constructions in the \
spacetime plane. The first postulate tells us how to draw light lines. The \
second postulate tells us how to relate proper times on an inertial line. \
Bondi triangles and the third postulate tells us how to reach off a single \
inertial line and relate intervals on different inertial lines. In principle \
we could measure ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"9ca85ff8-1215-4b63-85fe-e0d57ce6a1ca"],
 " just by measuring the Doppler shift. However, Section 2.7 contains a key \
theorem that will show us that clock intervals are related to areas in the \
spacetime plane. This will allow us to calculate ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"4788fa6f-022c-4d1d-bdc5-7af3e9e353bc"],
 " given two inertial lines."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f23e225a-b9aa-4fa4-bab8-10f5acffd004"]
}, Closed]],

