Cell[TextData[{
 "The light rectangle is called a ",
 StyleBox["causal area",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " by Brill and Jacobson. It is the intersection of the future light cone \
from ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"],ExpressionUUID->"6cb01b20-3124-4acf-98db-0401f0f1fa09"],
 " and the past light cone from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"dff61958-87d9-4db8-ade3-431f3a2ef355"],
 " (even though we haven't formally defined these yet.)"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1682ed9b-0e78-4237-9f2d-285d47be2f0b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It would be nice if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
    RowBox[{"2", "\[Theta]"}], "]"}], "/", 
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"2", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["s", "2"]}], ")"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4106ed96-5b85-4956-a4af-a060da73321e"],
 " was an invariant for all inertial lines because then we would have a \
single scale factor for our spacetime diagram and could relate proper time \
intervals to their associated causal areas everywhere. And indeed this is the \
case as we shall see in the next Section."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4a2ee18b-9aba-4fb7-a964-dc9c641651fb"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.7 Proper Times and Causal Areas - The Equal Area Theorem", \
"Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ad31972e-1c45-41a3-8cc2-229225212b39"],

Cell["\<\
We showed in the previous Section that along any single inertial line causal \
areas are proportional to the square of the proper time interval. Now we show \
that the proportionality constant is the same for all proper time intervals. \
Brill & Jacobson and Mermin both give proofs of this. I think the Mermin \
diagram and proof is slightly nicer. It directly uses the postulates given in \
Section 2.3.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"cfad3c8d-6b6f-483a-8801-5bff5c989563"],

