Cell[TextData[{
 "Two observer's clocks are set to zero as they pass at event ",
 Cell[BoxData["0"],ExpressionUUID->"6e41d1aa-7ee5-460f-921c-e71c0ac1b318"],
 ". At time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"e849e201-7a10-40a6-9f69-73d77b4d9efa"],
 " on each of their clocks they send photons towards each other. Because of \
the third postulate of relativity, they each receive their respective photon \
at the same time ",
 Cell[BoxData["T"],ExpressionUUID->"5477c036-dc35-45ab-802a-1ef31df02b1f"],
 " on their clocks. Because ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"2f504218-a88c-434b-8dbc-bc810753f0a7"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["T"],ExpressionUUID->"a76d6bd3-1dca-476b-8d23-61eb5508bbba"],
 " each appear on the same inertial line, the Euclidean distances on the line \
are proportional to the proper times (translation symmetry, second \
postulate). Let ",
 Cell[BoxData["a"],ExpressionUUID->"aa5525f3-00d4-4fb9-996d-5a39198d78b8"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData["b"],ExpressionUUID->"3e228e75-ca0a-4461-89af-68190e5836fa"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData["A"],ExpressionUUID->"f69e5f7c-d8f1-455c-9aaf-ddd00955badb"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["B"],ExpressionUUID->"d988d157-460d-4c74-a9a7-0bcf5f56f8cd"],
 " represent the Euclidean distances from the origin on the causal \
rectangles. Then ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"T", "/", "\[Tau]"}], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"a", "/", "b"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8b524fab-aa2a-4ee6-aaf6-d43914418c56"],
 " by similar triangles on observer 1 and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"T", "/", "\[Tau]"}], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"B", "/", "A"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "90d80d47-da59-4f4a-ab9a-29505d49089b"],
 " by similar triangles on observer 2. Then ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"a", " ", "A"}], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"b", " ", "B"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bc2265ef-0dd6-4792-8489-ad26754ccb36"],
 " and these are just the causal areas associated with the proper time ",
 Cell[BoxData["T"],ExpressionUUID->"b4cfe208-f2b7-4da6-b9c4-8f091161bcf3"],
 " for the first and second observer. Therefore, since the inertial lines and \
time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"7c75413e-9bbe-431f-bbe7-c050350cfce4"],
 " were arbitrary, equal proper times have equal causal areas."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c23a5662-d874-4019-87ca-02bcd1f41437"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Notice that this proof directly uses all three postulates. We used the \
first postulate in drawing the photon lines and the light rectangles. We used \
the second postulate in equating ratios of proper times to ratios of \
Euclidean distances. We used the third postulate to get both ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"d49efa5c-4e0c-4013-bae5-f7c6377844aa"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["T"],ExpressionUUID->"0f68b53c-9b54-4643-96af-f4212b8bb2b1"],
 " on each of the inertial lines so we could employ the second postulate. You \
should be able to see the Bondi triangles as well as the light rectangles."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"660d579a-9502-479d-a09e-5b54344afa42"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the above diagram the green area is the causal area for observer 1 and \
the blue area is the causal area for observer 2. If we vary the relative \
velocity between the two observers in an animation, we can see how an \
increasing ",
 Cell[BoxData["B"],ExpressionUUID->"0b8b8b87-b4c4-4546-a39c-3fc1d7ad5a7c"],
 " compensates for the decreasing ",
 Cell[BoxData["b"],ExpressionUUID->"efdd9a43-ee58-43fd-985c-440d1930aaaa"],
 ". Of course, the above proof of equal area applies to each of the frames."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"17a4556b-f180-4b98-84aa-a63929a7751e"],

