Cell[TextData[{
 "In the animation the light rays that complete the light rectangle ",
 Cell[BoxData["a0B"],ExpressionUUID->"9b00cbb1-2f92-4c72-9df4-a4ef809cf909"],
 " are drawn in. Notice that the causal area for the second observer is \
stretched in one direction and shrunk in the opposite direction so as to \
maintain a constant Euclidean area. This is the Lorentz transformation, which \
we will explore more completely in the next Section."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a1cbbf0a-03f5-488e-8737-54d7c5af29fa"],

Cell["We can now state the key result.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a98a66dc-5637-4b01-a8f5-3b6dec7db600"],

Cell["\<\
Equal Area Theorem
The square of the proper time interval along any inertial line segment is \
equal to the (Euclidean) area of its causal domain times a fixed \
proportionality constant.\
\>", "Text",
 CellFrame->True,
 FontFamily->"Helvetica",
 FontSize->16,
 FontWeight->"Bold",
 FontSlant->"Plain",ExpressionUUID->"09edc363-fbd3-46de-ab80-29be17317f2e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So there is only one proportionality constant for the entire diagram, which \
determines the scale of the diagram. We can write ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "2"], "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"K", " ", "area"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c610568d-b058-41a6-8587-6e4e057e845d"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData["K"],ExpressionUUID->"fef782a7-dc0b-48d1-84e9-29b7758af5dd"],
 " is the proportionality constant and ",
 Cell[BoxData["area"],ExpressionUUID->"734f4559-c4f1-4624-aca3-6acd3dad9161"],
 " is the causal area."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"466d2d74-03a2-4c0b-a496-d0c256d41906"],

Cell["\<\
We can then state a geometer's version of spacetime geometry. A geometer's \
version is in terms of the permissible transformations that leave the \
geometry invariant.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"82c2e405-08fa-493a-b538-d2846c50e99d"],

Cell["\<\
Postulate of Spacetime Geometry:
All permissible transformations of spacetime must preserve areas and must \
also leave unchanged,  or else interchange, the null directions.\
\>", "Text",
 CellFrame->True,
 FontFamily->"Helvetica",
 FontSize->16,
 FontWeight->"Bold",
 FontSlant->"Plain",ExpressionUUID->"5a9e9c9f-e806-4be1-a143-2c7494263bdc"],

Cell["\<\
Stated that way, we gain another insight into special relativity. The null \
directions are really and primarily a property of spacetime itself and only \
secondarily are they a property of light. Light and other massless particles \
exhibit the null directions but only because these directions are a property \
of spacetime. \
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d5f4f9a6-9c86-4cf5-b27f-9afac261ff46"],

Cell["\<\
Consequences of Spacetime Geometry:
Proper times and distances are invariant under all permissible \
transformations of spacetime. Hence, insofar as the laws of physics are \
expressed in proper times and distances they are the same for all observers.\
\>", "Text",
 CellFrame->True,
 FontFamily->"Helvetica",
 FontSize->16,
 FontWeight->"Bold",
 FontSlant->"Plain",ExpressionUUID->"92d24031-7f16-4fc7-9dd2-b87f74c9729b"],

Cell["\<\
Translations preserve both areas and the null directions. Reflection about a \
vertical line also preserve areas and null directions. There is one more \
allowed transformation that we consider in the next section.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4ee59c67-39f8-44ce-a515-88f661aa45d7"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2.8 The Lorentz Transformation", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"eeeb8699-dc17-4e08-864f-c55dc45b7cc2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "One way to preserve the null directions and areas in spacetime is to \
stretch it in the direction of the forward light rays by a factor ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"97499e2f-545c-43f7-b0eb-3e622a45a300"],
 " and to simultaneously shrink it in the direction of the backward rays by a \
factor of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", "k"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7f66b839-2c1e-4225-9ab4-f666ecb06460"],
 ". This can be done by putting coordinates ",
 Cell[BoxData["u"],ExpressionUUID->"7bee96de-0368-43bb-930a-9a5b3ae32998"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["v"],ExpressionUUID->"99acb8fa-006f-41c1-a41f-1128d0550107"],
 " along two intersecting light lines, expressing them in terms of ",
 Cell[BoxData["x"],ExpressionUUID->"9d6cb4eb-beb2-41af-b771-e2d01a9ad65b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData["t"],ExpressionUUID->"54d9f6d2-c5b9-4bda-9145-cae8f9651a4c"],
 ", performing the stretching and shrinking to obtain ",
 Cell[BoxData["up"],ExpressionUUID->"70146029-6711-4843-b828-ddc4c60f74fd"],
 " and ",
