Cell["\<\
The animation shows the effect of the transformation on a series of events, \
say a set of clock ticks for a stationary observer. The events are first \
stretched in the direction of the forward light line until they are twice as \
far from the backward light line. Then they are shrunk in the direction of \
the backward light line until they are only half as far from the forward \
light line. It is only the final position of the events that represents the \
actual transformation. The directions of the light lines are preserved as is \
required for relativity. One effect that we should note is that the Euclidean \
spacings of the clock ticks are changed by the transformation, but they do \
remain regularly spaced because they are just parallel projections from one \
line to another.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a8088e1e-7117-4f77-b3e5-766fef248498"],

Cell["\<\
Both the initial and final lines represent inertial world lines in spacetime. \
In the diagram above, the initial world line is at rest in the frame of the \
diagram. The final line represents motion to the right and hence it \
represents an observer moving with a nonzero velocity in the frame of the \
diagram. Hence Lorentz transformations correspond to changes in inertial \
frames.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4e906b54-04eb-4690-a81e-21b2591a68fa"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "No matter how much we stretch and shrink, the inertial line will never move \
beyond the light line. For ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"0", "<", "k", "<", "\[Infinity]"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7c7ecb99-ab10-4edc-bc0e-d46eaec74c76"],
 " the final line will always be within the region defined by the two light \
lines. For the Lorentz transformation, the speed of light is a limiting \
velocity."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"71d7b7e2-7acf-4eb8-88ba-c388a74e9b17"],

