Cell["2.9 Standard Areas, Minkowski Squares", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"10eddbdf-642f-45b6-b36d-12b7b0e01a4c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The equal area theorem shows that the square of proper intervals are \
proportional to the area of their causal domains. This proportionality \
constant is the same for the entire spacetime diagram and for all values of ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"8e06da17-17d1-4b43-afbc-140ee1ec9614"],
 ". All we have to do is mark out an interval of time for an observer at rest \
that corresponds to our unit, ",
 Cell[BoxData["T"],ExpressionUUID->"2ab3622f-2358-4dad-9802-8fa6c047a5f6"],
 ", of time. Our unit might be 1 second or 1 nanosecond or 1 meter (using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"c", "\[Equal]", "1"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "47ecd725-1597-4c36-8819-aa667ec1b9f2"],
 "). Let this be marked as a distance of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", " ", "L"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "42804030-64e7-47e1-a88c-2ac73aebe78e"],
 " on the diagram where ",
 Cell[BoxData["L"],ExpressionUUID->"09c06649-35ac-4e87-b48c-0ac3a7a53510"],
 " is the unit of distance on the paper. ",
 Cell[BoxData["L"],ExpressionUUID->"a9d732d7-03cc-485a-a9f1-3a3b3c92d9bf"],
 " might be centimeters or inches. This is illustrated in the following \
diagram."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9059ff6b-c0fb-4317-a2a7-f05105c5f900"],

