Cell[TextData[{
 "The causal domain, bounded by the light rectangle, is shown in blue. Its \
area is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   FractionBox["1", "2"], 
   SuperscriptBox["L", "2"]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "24de4ff4-1c5f-4dfe-a78b-6ef6645e7dcb"],
 ". Also shown is a red rectangle bounded by two parallel and vertical \
timelines and two parallel and horizontal spacelines in the frame of the rest \
observer for the diagram. This red area is called a ",
 StyleBox["Minkowski square",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " by Brill and Jacobson. We might also consider it to be the unit spacetime \
grid cell if we were to draw a grid of intersecting timelines and spacelines. \
It has an area of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["L", "2"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "63507749-cb29-4c16-a241-af5206ab4753"],
 ", twice that of the associated causal domain. A unit distance, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"42a3e1e9-266d-43d2-9610-811a9c75810a"],
 " is shown on the spaceline."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4dfe4135-1829-481b-bf3b-e9bb318b5bfa"],

Cell["\<\
Notice that the diagonals of the blue causal area are the same length in the \
diagram as the sides of the Minkowski square. The diagonals of the Minkowski \
square are light rays and are twice the length of the sides of the associated \
light rectangle. \
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"07b67e54-1169-4c25-b529-aff600875653"],

