Cell[TextData[{
 "Notice that the causal areas are always rectangular. Their diagonals are \
equal length but their sides are not generally equal length.  The diagonals \
make an angle ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Theta]"],ExpressionUUID->"489bd3ba-7de0-4253-892c-8091ea8d272e"],
 " with the forward light ray. On the other hand, the Minkowski 'squares' are \
generally rhombi. Their sides are equal length but their diagonals are not \
generally equal length. The sides make the same angle ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Theta]"],ExpressionUUID->"0d0d055a-99a9-44dc-a4b5-069937f452d9"],
 " with the forward light ray. We calculate the area of a causal area by the \
product of the sides. We calculate the area of a Minkowski square by 1/2 the \
product of its diagonals. The diagonals of the causal area are the sides of \
the Minkowski square."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"620dc3db-6fee-4ed1-819d-912b001b557c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For the general case, let ",
 Cell[BoxData["d"],ExpressionUUID->"df1f096b-c6bf-4ab6-9ee6-d9a4c30300a5"],
 " be the Euclidean length of the causal area diagonal, let ",
 Cell[BoxData["s"],ExpressionUUID->"1b739889-e144-4910-8689-de38d1da149d"],
 " be the scale factor that relates ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"98e9568a-70d2-438c-96fb-5fd46f652fb4"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData["d"],ExpressionUUID->"5ff31cc5-f0c1-4f9b-83a4-da25ac3f51af"],
 " and let ",
 Cell[BoxData["K"],ExpressionUUID->"9a3ccb2a-7eab-4716-bc95-52dd2924d48d"],
 " be the scale factor that relates ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\[Tau]", "2"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "87bd206f-7a27-4675-a746-bf86296074ba"],
 " to the causal area. The equations that relate these quantities are:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"be569001-88e1-4b51-88ab-77e68821c531"],

