Cell[TextData[{
 "When the causal domain is transformed to the 'standard position' its \
diagonal length is approximately ",
 Cell[BoxData["2.16"],ExpressionUUID->"f54b40d3-03f5-4e83-aaff-aa826194285e"],
 " by the scale. Since we can directly compare the diagonal lengths, we don't \
have to calculate the area. ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Equal]", "2.16"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d288ab6b-3bd9-4b02-9be8-4797f6b899ce"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7b83c7a4-a600-4ca1-9982-dd48c8d605f9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "However, we would seldom actually calculate an interval by measuring an \
area and using ",
 Cell[BoxData["K"],ExpressionUUID->"22add49c-9a22-4929-a803-b80ee42e6e75"],
 ", or doing such a graphical transformation. Rather, we would use the \
equations of special relativity and calculate algebraically. Section ",
 "3.10",
 " presents a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "SRSolve"],ExpressionUUID->"5bfbc952-ef26-4e07-9b12-eea1803808f6"],
 " routine, which in conjunction with the Lorentz functions allows us to \
calculate most quantities of interest. Nor are we especially interested in \
what values ",
 Cell[BoxData["s"],ExpressionUUID->"c0697e56-6ee9-4333-9f4a-853d8fd1dd9a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Theta]"],ExpressionUUID->"077f512a-da6f-4aac-9bcc-4e3600d5a0be"],
 " actually have in the earlier diagram."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"16bfea1e-3a33-46b7-8f85-902a0d2c99bf"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Nevertheless, the area relation and the expression for the constant ",
 Cell[BoxData["K"],ExpressionUUID->"2ca7f0bc-0e48-4179-ac74-c946adf0d172"],
 " are useful in geometric derivations and proofs."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"26443d6d-e572-47dc-9f57-e026438e3584"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

