Cell[TextData[{
 "The black parallel lines are the world lines of three parallel observers \
for various values of ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"eb593c05-de8d-4741-a811-b15146fccf93"],
 ". From the viewpoint of the implied observer whose world line is vertical \
they represent uniform motion to the left or right at various speeds. They \
also represent the time axes for each of the three observers. Once the clocks \
have been synchronized by the procedure described above, the middle observer \
would consider the middle point of his world line to be simultaneous with the \
events of reflection of the two photons. Therefore the other (greenish) \
diagonal of the light rectangle will be a line of simultaneity for the middle \
observer. If we take the center of the light rectangle to be the spacetime \
origin then this other diagonal will be his space axis (since events on it \
occur simultaneously in his frame). The line of simultaneity for a stationary \
observer is the lightly drawn horizontal line. It is clear that simultaneity \
is a relative concept."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"20af0610-6e96-494c-8f3b-bf71c8295b27"],

Cell["\<\
This demonstration of the relativity of simultaneity is, I believe, far \
simpler than the complicated diagrams and convoluted reasoning associated \
with lightning strikes at two ends of a spaceship, or Einstein's railroad \
car. Animation allows us to directly see the moving line of simultaneity.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4d99f137-caa7-4a15-9294-fb089ed963d8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As the above animation illustrates, if we have an inertial line for an \
observer, which represents the observer's time axis, then we can immediately \
draw the observer's spatial axis. All we have to do is draw a light rectangle \
for two equally spaced points about his time origin and then draw the ",
 StyleBox["other",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " diagonal. Furthermore, if we regard space and time axes to be 'orthogonal' \
then we regard these two diagonals as orthogonal in the spacetime plane."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a6c3af69-d704-4be8-b48e-665badfc2191"],

Cell["\<\
Furthermore, the causal area associated with one diagonal of a light \
rectangle (a time interval) is the same as that associated with the other \
diagonal (a space interval).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c8ea74aa-c684-4ece-8fdf-893cec2f02bf"]
}, Closed]],

