Cell[TextData[{
 "The Bondi triangle, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "O\[Sigma]\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"1dedd355-0cdf-4fa3-898b-e7da3be04688"],
 " is shown in yellow. The Minkowski square built on the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"f301eb3e-a17d-484b-bc05-8b4251013457"],
 " interval is also show as the red rhombus. As ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"0fa37267-71d9-4e45-a178-30535cf65d78"],
 " increases ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"466c62cc-6040-4f2e-8176-54c71ecf3505"],
 " decreases to maintain ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Equal]", 
   RowBox[{"k", " ", "\[Sigma]"}]}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "57b2465c-a51c-4202-907a-e83c78bcfa0b"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6bc64b72-147c-47a4-9709-63337a1afbf5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Bondi ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"b137c445-99b2-4c30-a2ca-4afbdb5861bf"],
 " factor is thus a wonderful simplifying concept for special relativity. It \
is very easy to understand and visualize the Lorentz transformation in terms \
of ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"b1e2b9ca-3854-412c-814d-7b68361d44c6"],
 " - much more difficult in terms of velocity ",
 Cell[BoxData["v"],ExpressionUUID->"36e80804-7c21-48d0-9a54-2268685f7637"],
 ". (For example Taylor & Wheeler (3) devote a whole chapter to deriving the \
Lorentz transformation with a fair amount of algebra.) The coefficients in \
the Lorentz equations are in terms of only one variable, ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"a6bf9f8b-bfc5-4d13-b445-84e744efd279"],
 ", instead of two, ",
 Cell[BoxData["v"],ExpressionUUID->"a44de9f9-18e6-4f6f-a11f-e3bd02aba21a"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Gamma]"],ExpressionUUID->"d96daced-77f4-4253-8a54-b455f40c41c2"],
 ", and there are no square roots involved - directly or hidden. There is \
also a simple symmetry, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", "1"}]],ExpressionUUID->"18983442-31bc-479c-adf0-04dd45af683e"],
 "s on the diagonal and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1"}]],ExpressionUUID->"86af0697-fb00-4c80-8845-6d44b80f273b"],
 "s on the off diagonal. That this is the same ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"03de73b8-f8d0-42b2-8db7-a90e38061283"],
 " as appears in the Doppler shift and all the constructions involving Bondi \
triangles is a nice unification. Ultimately we want to relate ",
 Cell[BoxData["k"],ExpressionUUID->"591b92da-2851-4298-8aa1-8c7d48bd941f"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData["v"],ExpressionUUID->"cd7b4624-0d31-4e62-92ea-03abed8ce131"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Gamma]"],ExpressionUUID->"93093f1a-e1dc-47d4-a66b-04dd4a007e86"],
 " and other quantities. This is done in Section 3.4 and an ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "SRSolve"],ExpressionUUID->"b74997b1-21ba-408f-b44e-d86551f6fc91"],
 " routine for calculating various relationships is demonstrated in Section ",
 "3.10",
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dfc6a020-de5c-4bb6-a3ac-b7206bc62cc8"]
}, Closed]],

