Cell[TextData[{
 "A particle at rest travels from ",
 Cell[BoxData["A"],ExpressionUUID->"21ef7666-2697-4f8c-b811-cc187fcd7f9c"],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData["B"],ExpressionUUID->"ceca4b02-5de3-4bd1-85da-e9dc96a490e9"],
 " in proper time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"f2c71b6e-3ddd-4429-8f0a-543c7dc49649"],
 ". If the particle is moving so it reaches the point ",
 Cell[BoxData["C"],ExpressionUUID->"e288587f-37c0-4558-b896-7483af1ada57"],
 " in the same coordinate time, then its proper time ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"2dac8b75-c3c2-4196-9e4d-8c573c7ffa6c"],
 " is less than ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"cd48f33b-e41d-43ae-b0fe-3811409ba1b9"],
 ". The blue area is the causal domain of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"7390d5e6-ccd9-4a32-af76-fc2dc6665d53"],
 ". The green area is the causal domain of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"e03097c1-d37c-4e2b-901b-913dd6be9e22"],
 ". Comparing the nonoverlap regions we see that the green portion is always \
less than the blue portion because ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"BD", "\[Equal]", "DC"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "04f2546e-28d6-48f0-88e1-dae1891f7d42"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"CF", "<", "BE", "\[Equal]", "EA"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "84d42b8b-278c-4993-b71f-6fcb98f6f101"],
 " for all points ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"C", "\[NotEqual]", "B"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dd90f95a-2a8f-4524-9a4b-811ae42fce45"],
 ". In fact, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Tau]", "\[Rule]", "0"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9822d8ff-3868-4ccb-af66-a6546deee7c7"],
 " as the inertial line approaches the null direction."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f9dfffe7-6138-46cd-b36a-02ec957bb970"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A beginning student might ask why the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"61b6386d-8ecd-4cad-9404-84a3b170f6c9"],
 " observer can't be thought of as startionary and then ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[Sigma]", "<", "\[Tau]"}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7aac9550-84d0-4d1f-931f-2bf12c9ba9f1"],
 "? There is not a paradox here. The point ",
 Cell[BoxData["C"],ExpressionUUID->"2a71f27b-a7b3-4eb5-b471-89c178161b34"],
 " moves along a constant time line for the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"56eb0525-b8e3-40a0-aa1e-7e4c2382004a"],
 " observer and it definitely is not a constant time line for the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Tau]"],ExpressionUUID->"e47f8e3a-4aa1-4036-94fc-4296cf12033c"],
 " observer. The situtation is not symmetrical. The constant time line is \
attached to only one of the observers."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"69d99f39-1d56-4d47-973b-05a35257a38b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In special relativity it is often easier to derive a theorem or \
relationship in a particular inertial frame. In the above case it was the \
frame in which the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
 "\[Sigma]"],ExpressionUUID->"b9da9177-0aed-4c3d-a240-806d89d0b077"],
 " observer was stationary. Since the Lorentz transformation preserves areas \
the relationship will be true in all inertial frames. In the following \
animation, the entire diagram has been Lorentz transformed."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"932ac0a2-c493-4245-9584-5b3d7474fd76"],

