Cell[TextData[{
 "The classic demonstration of time dilation is the decay of unstable \
particles in flight. In the following animation a group of ",
 Cell[BoxData["100"],ExpressionUUID->"3796409d-3794-41ce-851c-09bd90ea70b9"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\[Pi]", "+"]],ExpressionUUID->
  "df78dc53-caee-4807-8d8f-e3f157232814"],
 " mesons are created in an accelerator on the left. They fly off as a group \
at a speed such that the time dilation is a factor of ",
 Cell[BoxData["10"],ExpressionUUID->"7e11f1ad-5dd8-4c95-90c8-10f763fbf309"],
 ". The half life of the mesons is ",
 Cell[BoxData["18"],ExpressionUUID->"3c4f4f4d-6afa-4c7f-90d2-d9f1ed7290d2"],
 " nanoseconds. The animation follows the fate of the mesons for ",
 Cell[BoxData["90"],ExpressionUUID->"3ec9a0ad-4a11-47ff-9351-b5e3efc5903d"],
 " nanoseconds in the lab frame. Mermin calls the unit of distance that light \
travels in one nanosecond a foot. It is almost the English foot. He calls it \
a foot because it sounds like the Greek \[Phi]\[Omega]\[Tau]\[Omicron]\
\[Stigma] for light and he thinks that the English foot will eventually \
disappear in advance civilizations. Thus he can usurp the unit. But I think \
as long as humans have feet the old unit will stay around and in the meantime \
there is room for confusion. I therefore call the distance that light travels \
in one nanosecond a phoot."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2242b3fc-6c0f-40bb-a0a8-3269310dbe45"],

