Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["3.11 Einstein's Train, Einstein's Genius", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"82539f9b-911e-449c-adcc-93035a222daf"],

Cell["\<\
Several mathematicians worked out much of Einstein's mathematics before he \
did (10). That is why we have the Lorentz transformation and not the Einstein \
transformation. But they did not understand the physical significance of the \
mathematics and Einstein did. Most of all, Einstein understood that we had to \
change our conception of time.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e39eb0cf-adbd-466d-86f7-f094c1854167"],

Cell["\<\
Einstein presented an argument showing that we must give up the concept of \
simultaneity and with it the concept of Newton's universal time. Universal \
time is simply incompatible with the invariance of the velocity of light, his \
first postulate.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b2c96cbc-b33f-420e-a0a0-2cd26bec4305"],

Cell["\<\
This leads to the gedanken experiment concerning 'Einstein's Train' (although \
in Einstein's paper he actually talks about a moving rod). Today rockets are \
often used. The object of this thought experiment is to convince us that \
universal time must be abandoned and we must pay attention to the readings of \
individual clocks - as we have done throughout this notebook. But I must \
admit that I often find the textbook presentation of this argument to be very \
confusing, so much so that it often stands as a barrier to understanding \
relativity. That is why I dispensed with it in the main development of the \
theory and didn't discuss the relativity of simutaneity until Section 3.1. \
Part of the difficulty is in presenting simple graphics that clearly show the \
points at issue. Animation helps and here is an attempt.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d0f35eb1-736c-4b81-9799-5c5f0fe14104"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We imagine a train, or rocket, standing still. There are two photon sources \
at each end of the train. There is an observer at the center of the train. \
There is also an observer outside the train. At the same time, in the frame \
of the train, the two photon sources send photons toward the center observer. \
Because he is equidistant between the photon sources he will receive the \
photons at the same time. We have three events: ",
 Cell[BoxData["E1"],ExpressionUUID->"fd2292d2-d32d-414b-b1cb-e3eb71b8898a"],
 " is the event of the left photon source emitting its photon; ",
 Cell[BoxData["E2"],ExpressionUUID->"330b97c7-a024-4559-8461-ae6654423df1"],
 " is the event of the right photon source emitting its photon. ",
 Cell[BoxData["E3"],ExpressionUUID->"332fd053-2b35-4674-bdc7-a2ff2cca0264"],
 " is the event of the central observer receiving the two photons."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d0e61a75-2a7a-4090-8341-a6ce373867cc"],

Cell["\<\
Now, what happens if the train is moving to the left or right? If we assume \
the universal time of Newton, we obtain the following picture as seen by the \
observer outside the train.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"46647ed6-61d8-4f00-9c6e-d07ab08b38bb"],

